properties.text: Playing in front of 93,000 spectators at Wembley (including the Queen), England beat West Germany to win the tournament in 1966. Football has not made it home since, but stills holds a place in Britons' hearts and chants.
The 'Swinging Sixties' saw a cultural explosion of British music and fashion. Social changes also gathered pace with the passing of the Race Relations Act and the decriminilisation of homosexuality.

Gaining popularity with 'Love Me Do' in 1962, the Liverpool lads topped the charts for much of the decade, until their breakup in 1970. The Beatles are the best-selling music artists of all time, with 600 million record sales.

Published for the first time in 1964, The Sun was billed as a 'radical' alternative to The Mirror. Later it would be bought by Rupert Murdoch and become the UK's most popular newspaper across the week.
